   pages = {132-148},
   note = {Export Date: 22 April 2019},
   abstract = {The changes in the Earth’s climate could cause, in the next 50 to 100 years, deep and irreversible alterations to both natural and human environments (Ferrara, 2005; IPCC, 2007; EEA-JRC-WHO, 2008; IPCC, 2014). The ensuing rise of extreme weather events, along with the growth of human population and infrastructures in vulnerable areas, has been given much attention by scientists, policy-makers and citizens. This increasing interest has promoted research on potential future climate impact scenarios, in terms of both risks and opportunities, and strategies of mitigation and adaptation. Despite the fact that climatic variations are a normal expression of the dynamic nature of planet Earth, the current speed of these changes does not seem to find precedents in the recent climate record of the planet (IPCC, 2007; 2013). These accelerated changes have a cascade effects with many effects at both the global and local level. The amount and type of consequences are closely dependent on local ecosystems and differ strongly across spatial scales, and depend on vulnerability and adaptive capacity of the residing communities. The identification of future climate impact is pivotal to understanding how a society has to prepare in order to deal with emerging climate hazards and risks (IPCC, 2007; MATT, 2007; EEA-JRC-WHO, 2008; IPCC, 2013). © 2018 selection and editorial matter, Giuseppe Forino, Sara Bonati and Lina Maria Calandra.},
