   abstract = {This chapter provides an overview of the current status of monitoring and evaluation (M&E) of government-led climate change adaptation interventions in Bangladesh. The chapter discusses the M&E framework and practice of the two major climate funds in Bangladesh, the Bangladesh Climate Change Trust Fund (BCCTF) and the Bangladesh Climate Change Resilience Fund (BCCRF). It finds for both funds that the constellation of stakeholders and their coordination, as well as the lack of availability of reliable data and the institutional framework have an influence on the effectiveness of M&E and therefore on their ability to ensure that funds reach the most vulnerable communities. The Community Climate Change Project (CCCP) is introduced as a case study to demonstrate how result-based-monitoring (RBM) could be utilized in climate change adaptation projects. The CCCP used a multi-tiered monitoring approach, built on trusted partners, and had prior experience of working within the selected communities. It thereby allowed stakeholder representation from multiple levels. This enabled experimental learning during the M&E process. It is expected that the analysis provided in the chapter will inform current discourses on M&E for adaptation interventions. © 2018 by Nova Science Publishers, Inc. All rights reserved.},
