   pages = {394-399},
   note = {Export Date: 22 April 2019},
   abstract = {There is growing international recognition of the need for practical guidance on evaluating risks and adapting freshwaters to climate change, drawing on both field and model evidence. This special section of Area demonstrates the varied ways in which geographers, environmental and social scientists, engineers and resource managers are beginning to address these urgent needs. This editorial considers the long history of field experimentation and measurement that has informed professional practice in catchment and water quality management. We assert that comparable levels of investment and commitment are now needed to guide adaptations to climate change. The research within the special section reflects two contrasting perspectives: (i) top-down, macro-scale, climatic and non-climatic risk assessments for freshwaters and (ii) bottom-up, micro-scale experimentation, involving adaptation measures at the river reach and habitat level. We emphasise that greater efforts are required to integrate the results of research at these contrasting scales to deliver benefits that are robust to the large uncertainty associated with climate projections. © 2012 The Authors. Area © 2012 Royal Geographical Society (with the Institute of British Geographers).},
